# Data quality checklist — {{PROJECT_NAME}}

Scan a new or updated dataset for the common "bad data" problems before you build on it, using this adaptation of the Quartz bad-data taxonomy. The checks are grouped by who is best placed to fix each problem — your source, you, a subject-matter expert, or a programmer — because knowing whose problem it is determines what to do next. Record what you find and how you handled it in `DATA-DICTIONARY.md`'s known-issues section so downstream users are not surprised. This is about whether the data can be trusted at all; `docs/checklists/data-bulletproofing-checklist.md` is the pre-publication reconciliation that follows.

## Issues your SOURCE should fix

- [ ] Values are missing where you expected data, and the gaps are unexplained.
- [ ] Zeros are standing in for missing values (or vice versa), so absence is silently counted as a real measurement.
- [ ] Suspicious sentinel values appear (e.g. `65535`, `-1`, `9999`, `1900-01-01`) that actually mean "unknown."
- [ ] Spelling or capitalization is inconsistent across records, fragmenting what should be one category.
- [ ] Date and number formats are inconsistent (e.g. `MM/DD` mixed with `DD/MM`, or thousands separators in some rows).
- [ ] Units or essential metadata are missing, so a column of numbers has no defined meaning.
- [ ] The data looks truncated — for example cut off at exactly 65,536 rows by the tool that exported it.

## Issues YOU should fix

- [ ] Text is garbled by an encoding or line-ending mismatch (mojibake, stray characters, broken rows).
- [ ] The data only exists inside PDFs or scanned images and has to be extracted before use.
- [ ] The data is at the wrong aggregation level for the question — too coarse, or aggregated when you need the units.
- [ ] Human data entry is inconsistent (free-text where codes were expected, ad hoc abbreviations).
- [ ] Figures are not adjusted for inflation, or a seasonal series is compared without accounting for seasonality.
- [ ] The sample is non-random or otherwise biased in a way that does not support the claim you want to make.
- [ ] The margin of error is large or unknown, so apparent differences may be noise.

## Issues an EXPERT should weigh in on

- [ ] The author or collecting body is of uncertain trustworthiness or has an interest in the result.
- [ ] The collection methodology is opaque, so you cannot tell what the numbers actually measure.
- [ ] Figures show false precision — more decimal places or specificity than the method could support.
- [ ] There are inexplicable outliers that no one can account for.
- [ ] The analysis shows signs of p-hacking — results that survive only under one of many possible specifications.
- [ ] An index or composite masks the underlying variation that matters for interpretation.

## Issues a PROGRAMMER should help with

- [ ] The data needs to be re-aggregated or reshaped programmatically (e.g. rolled up from records, or pivoted).
- [ ] OCR or text extraction needs tuning to recover the data reliably from scans or PDFs.

